      <body>
         
            
               <p>Long-time pastor of a Presbyterian congregation in <placeName>Norwich</placeName>,
                        <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers1991.xml"/>Taylor</persName> assumed the
                  role of tutor at <placeName>Warrington Academy</placeName> in late <date when="1757">1757</date>. He was a prominent voice among the 'rational
                  dissenters', and <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>'s most extended apologetic treatise was a response to
                        <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers1991.xml"/>Taylor</persName>'s <hi rend="italic">Scripture-Doctrine of Original Sin</hi> (<date when="1740">1740</date>). For more details on <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers1991.xml"/>Taylor</persName> and this work, see the
                  editorial introduction to <persName>
                            <ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>'s <hi rend="italic">Doctrine of Original Sin</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi>, 12:117–54. See <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>.</p>
            
         
